:["English: habitational name from any of various places called Burley, for example in Hampshire, Rutland, Shropshire, and Yorkshire, from Old English <i>burh</i> ‘fortified manor, stronghold’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’.","English: variant of   Birley  .","Americanized form of Swiss German <b>Bürli</b>: from a diminutive of <i>būr</i> ‘peasant, farmer’ (see   Bauer  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Burleigh","meanings":["English: variant of   Burley  ."]},{"name":"Berley","meanings":["English (Yorkshire): variant of   Burley  . This surname is now rare in Britain. It may also be a variant of   Birley  .","Americanized form of Swiss German <b>Beerli</b>, <b>Berli</b>, or <b>Berly</b>, and probably also of their South German cognate   Behrle   or of some other similar (like-sounding) surname. Compare   Barley  ."]},{"name":"Birley","meanings":["English: habitational name from Birley in Ecclesfield (Yorkshire), East or North Bierley (Yorkshire), or Birley (Derbyshire)."]},{"name":"Burlew","meanings":["Probably a variant of   Burley   1 or 2."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":10,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705191,"age":35,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705192,"age":48,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705193,"age":57,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"When William Burley was born about 1280, in England, his father, Sir John de Burley Earl of Broomcroft, was 29 and his mother, Alice Pembridge, was 21. He died in 1358, at the age of 79."},"et":{"about 1280–1358":"umbes 1280–1358","1280–1358":"1280–1358","1280–Female":"1280–Surnud","1285–Female":"1285–Surnud","1305–1383":"1305–1383","1252–Male":"1252–Surnud","1260–1303":"1260–1303","about 1280":"umbes 1280","1252":"1252","1285":"1285","1383":"1383","1260":"1260","1280":"1280","1290":"1290","1305":"1305","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1303":"1303","1358":"1358","1453":"1453","1276":"1276","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Burley, Herefordshire, England":"Herefordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England"},"fi":{"about 1280–1358":"noin 1280–1358","1280–1358":"1280–1358","1280–Female":"1280–Kuollut","1285–Female":"1285–Kuollut","1305–1383":"1305–1383","1252–Male":"1252–Kuollut","1260–1303":